 Update</article-title></title-group><contrib-group><contrib contrib-type="author"><name name-style="western"><surname>Carey</surname><given-names initials="RM">Robert M.</given-names></name><degrees>MD, FAHA</degrees></contrib><contrib contrib-type="author"><name name-style="western"><surname>Wright</surname><given-names initials="JT">Jackson T.</given-names><suffix>Jr.</suffix></name><degrees>MD, PhD, FAHA</degrees></contrib><contrib contrib-type="author"><name name-style="western"><surname>Taler</surname><given-names initials="SJ">Sandra J.</given-names></name><degrees>MD, FAHA</degrees></contrib><contrib contrib-type="author"><name name-style="western"><surname>Whelton</surname><given-names initials="PK">Paul K.</given-names></name><degrees>MB, MD, MSc, FAHA</degrees></contrib><aff id="A1">Department of Medicine, University of Virginia Health System, Charlottesville, VA (RMC); Department of Medicine, Case-Western Reserve University School of Medicine, Cleveland, OH (JTW Jr); Department of Medicine, Mayo Clinic College of Medicine, Rochester, MN (SJT); and the Departments of Epidemiology and Medicine, Tulane University, New Orleans, LA (PKW)</aff></contrib-group><author-notes><corresp id="CR1">Address for correspondence: Dr. Robert M. Carey, P.O. Box 801414, University of Virginia Health System, Charlottesville, VA 22908-1414; telephone: 434-924-5510; fax: 982-3626; <email>rmc4c@virginia.edu</email>.</corresp></author-notes><pub-date pub-type="epub"><day>01</day><month>4</month><year>2021</year></pub-date><pub-date pub-type="ppub"><day>02</day><month>4</month><year>2021</year></pub-date><volume>128</volume><issue>7</issue><issue-id pub-id-type="pmc-issue-id">379383</issue-id><fpage>827</fpage><lpage>846</lpage><pub-history><event event-type="nihms-submitted"><date><day>04</day><month>03</month><year>2021</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-release"><date><day>02</day><month>04</month><year>2022</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-live"><date><day>02</day><month>04</month><year>2022</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-released-under-embargo"><date><day>10</day><month>04</month><year>2021</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-last-change"><date iso-8601-date="2024-06-17 01:25:18.230"><day>17</day><month>06</month><year>2024</year></date></event></pub-history><self-uri xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" content-type="pmc-pdf" xlink:href="nihms-1677952.pdf"/><abstract id="ABS1"><p id="P1">Several important findings bearing on the prevention, detection and management of hypertension have been reported since publication of the 2017 American College of Cardiology (ACC)/American Heart Association (AHA) Blood Pressure (BP) Guideline. This review summarizes and places in context the results of relevant observational studies, randomized clinical trials and meta-analyses published between January, 2018 and March, 2021. Topics covered include BP measurement, patient evaluation for secondary hypertension, cardiovascular disease (CVD) risk assessment and BP threshold for drug therapy, lifestyle and pharmacologic management, treatment target BP goal, management of hypertension in older adults, diabetes mellitus, chronic kidney disease, resistant hypertension, and optimization of care using patient, provider and health system approaches. Presenting new information in each of these areas has the potential to increase hypertension awareness, treatment and control which remain essential for the prevention of CVD and mortality in the future.</p></abstract><kwd-group><kwd>blood pressure</kwd><kwd>hypertension</kwd><kwd>prevention</kwd><kwd>treatment</kwd><kwd>diagnosis</kwd><kwd>High Blood Pressure</kwd></kwd-group><custom-meta-group><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-qastatus</meta-name><meta-value>0</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-live</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-embargo</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-m